es the meaning of ‘9 November’ changed, becoming increasingly contested between rival parties, military experts and scholars. This book examines how the debate on the revolution has evolved from August 1919 to the present day. It takes the reader through the ideological battles of the 1920s and 30s into the equally politicised historical writing of the cold war period. It ends with a consideration of the marginalisation of the revolution in academic research since the 1980s, and its revival from 2010.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aManchester Digital Textbooks. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aHISTORY / Revolutionary.2bisacsh  aEast Germany.  aImperial Germany.  aMarxism.  aWeimar republic.  aWest Germany.  acold war.  afirst world war.  ahistoriography.  arevolution.  asecond world war.1 aStibbe, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2023 eBook-Packagez9783111206455oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615750840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526157508423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526157508/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2023